Project Overview

The SMS Spam Classifier is a machine learning model designed to distinguish between spam and legitimate (ham) messages. By analyzing text features and patterns, the model helps identify unwanted or fraudulent messages, improving user experience and security.

Project Goal

The primary goal of this project is to develop a machine learning model that accurately classifies SMS messages as either spam or ham (legitimate). Spam messages often contain fraudulent content, phishing attempts, or unwanted advertisements, making them a nuisance and a potential security risk for users.

By building this classifier, we aim to:

  • Enhance message filtering: Reduce the likelihood of users receiving spam messages.
  • Improve security: Identify and prevent phishing or scam messages.
  • Automate detection: Provide an efficient, scalable solution for spam filtering.

The variable we are modeling is the spam label (binary: spam or ham) based on message content. Understanding the patterns in spam messages allows for better classification, ultimately improving communication safety and user experience.

Data Description

The SMS Spam Collection is a set of SMS tagged messages that have been collected for SMS Spam research. It contains one set of SMS messages in English of 5,574 messages, tagged acording being ham (legitimate) or spam.

The source of the data is Kaggle.

Data Preprocessing / Text Preprocessing

  1. Lower Case
  2. Tokenization
  3. Removing Special Characters
  4. Remove Stop Words and Punctuations
  5. Stemming (dance/dancing/danced - take only dance since meaning is same)
In[38]:
def transform_text(text):
  text = text.lower() # lowercase
  text = nltk.word_tokenize(text) # tokenization

  y = [] # remove special characters
  for i in text:
    if i.isalnum():
      y.append(i)

  text = y[:] # remove stop words and punctuations
  y.clear()
  for i in text:
    if i not in stopwords.words('english') and i not in string.punctuation:
      y.append(i)

  text = y[:] # stemming
  y.clear()
  for i in text:
    y.append(ps.stem(i))

  return " ".join(y)

    "Logistic Regression": {"C": [0.1, 1, 10]},
    "kNN": {"n_neighbors": [3, 5, 7]},
    "Decision Tree": {"max_depth": [5, 10, 20]},
    "Random Forest": {"n_estimators": [50, 100], "max_depth": [5, 10]},
    "Gradient Boosting": {"n_estimators": [50, 100], "learning_rate": [0.1, 0.01]},
    "SVC": {"C": [0.1, 1, 10], "kernel": ["linear", "rbf"]}
}

Model Descriptions

(i) Logistic Regression

Type: Parametric model

Tuning parameters: Regularization strength (L1/L2 penalty via C in sklearn)

Inference possible? Yes, interpretable coefficients

Performs variable selection? Yes, if L1 (Lasso) regularization is used

Standardization needed? Yes (for numerical stability)

(ii) k-Nearest Neighbors (kNN)

Type: Non-parametric model

Tuning parameters: Number of neighbors (k), distance metric (Euclidean, Manhattan)

Inference possible? No, it makes predictions based on neighbors, not learned parameters

Performs variable selection? No

Standardization needed? Yes (kNN is sensitive to feature scaling)

(iii) Decision Tree

Type: Non-parametric model

Tuning parameters: Maximum depth, minimum samples per leaf

Inference possible? Yes (interpretable, but prone to overfitting)

Performs variable selection? Yes (implicitly selects important features)

Standardization needed? No (trees are not affected by feature scaling)

(iv) Random Forest

Type: Ensemble of decision trees (non-parametric)

Tuning parameters: Number of trees (n_estimators), depth, minimum samples per split

Inference possible? Limited interpretability, feature importance ranking available

Performs variable selection? Yes

Standardization needed? No

(v) Gradient Boosting (XGBoost)

Type: Ensemble learning (boosting)

Tuning parameters: Learning rate, number of estimators, max depth, min samples per leaf

Inference possible? Limited

Performs variable selection? Yes

Standardization needed? No

(vi) Support Vector Classifier (SVC)

Type: Parametric if linear kernel, non-parametric if RBF

Tuning parameters: Kernel type, C (regularization), gamma (for RBF kernel)

Inference possible? Limited

Performs variable selection? No

Standardization needed? Yes (SVMs are sensitive to feature scaling)

In[55]:
# Dictionary to store results
results = {}

# Evaluate each model
for model_name, model in models.items():
    print(f"\n=== Evaluating {model_name} ===")

    # Predictions
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test)

    # Calculate metrics
    accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
    precision = precision_score(y_test, y_pred)
    recall = recall_score(y_test, y_pred)
    f1 = f1_score(y_test, y_pred)

    # Store results
    results[model_name] = {
        "Accuracy": accuracy,
        "Precision": precision,
        "Recall": recall,
        "F1-Score": f1
    }

    # Print detailed report
    print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred))

# Identify the best model based on F1-score (or another metric if necessary)
best_model_name = max(results, key=lambda x: results[x]["F1-Score"])
best_model = models[best_model_name]

print(f"\n Best model selected: {best_model_name} (based on F1-score)")

# Store metrics for each model
accuracy_scores = []
precision_scores = []
f1_scores = []
recall_scores = []
model_names = []

# Evaluate each model
for model_name, model in models.items():
    print(f"\n=== Evaluating {model_name} ===")

    # Predictions
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test)

    # Calculate metrics
    accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
    precision = precision_score(y_test, y_pred)
    f1 = f1_score(y_test, y_pred)
    recall = recall_score(y_test, y_pred)

    # Append metrics
    accuracy_scores.append(accuracy)
    precision_scores.append(precision)
    f1_scores.append(f1)
    recall_scores.append(recall)
    model_names.append(model_name)

# Create DataFrame
performance_df = pd.DataFrame({
    'Algorithm': model_names,
    'Accuracy': accuracy_scores,
    'Precision': precision_scores,
    'F1_Score': f1_scores,
    'Recall': recall_scores
})

# Sort DataFrame by Precision (descending order)
performance_df_sorted = performance_df.sort_values('F1_Score', ascending=False)

Best Model Selection

For evaluating the models, I will consider accuracy and F1-score, as both are crucial for an SMS spam classifier.

Why Accuracy and F1-Score?

  • Accuracy gives an overall measure of correctness but can be misleading in imbalanced datasets (if spam is only 10% of the data, a model that predicts "not spam" all the time will have 90% accuracy).

  • F1-score balances precision (avoiding false positives) and recall (catching all spam messages), making it more reliable for spam detection.

Final Decision: Why SVC?

  • Best F1-Score It effectively captures spam while minimizing false positives.

  • Best Accuracy It generalizes well across messages.

  • Robust to Imbalanced Data Unlike simple accuracy-based models, SVC optimizes the margin, making it resilient to class imbalances.

Best Model Details - Support Vector Classifier

The best model is SVC (Support Vector Classifier), and based on the evaluation metrics, we can interpret its performance and features as follows:

SVC Model Performance Metrics:

Precision: For spam messages (class 1), the model has a precision of 0.96, meaning that 96% of messages classified as spam are indeed spam. For ham messages (class 0), it has a precision of 0.98, indicating that 98% of messages classified as ham are indeed ham.

Recall: The recall for spam messages (class 1) is 0.85, meaning 85% of actual spam messages are correctly identified as spam. For ham messages (class 0), the recall is 0.99, showing that 99% of actual ham messages are correctly identified.

F1-Score: The F1-score for spam messages is 0.90, indicating a good balance between precision and recall for spam classification. The F1-score for ham messages is 0.99, reflecting excellent classification of ham messages.

Accuracy: The overall accuracy of 0.97 means the model correctly classifies 97% of all messages.

Macro Average: The macro average F1-score is 0.94, which gives equal weight to both classes. The model performs very well overall but slightly better for ham messages.

Weighted Average: The weighted F1-score of 0.97 takes the class distribution into account, again showing excellent performance.

Key Observations:

Recall for Spam (0.85) is a bit lower than for Ham (0.99), suggesting that the model misses some spam messages (false negatives). This is typical for models where recall is more difficult to achieve due to the class imbalance (there are fewer spam messages in the dataset).

Precision for Spam (0.96) is relatively high, meaning that the majority of messages predicted as spam are indeed spam.

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA

# Apply PCA to reduce dimensionality to 2 components for visualization
pca = PCA(n_components=2)
X_train_pca = pca.fit_transform(X_train) # Removed .toarray()

# Fit the model to the reduced data
best_model.fit(X_train_pca, y_train)

# Plot decision boundary
xx, yy = np.meshgrid(np.linspace(X_train_pca[:, 0].min(), X_train_pca[:, 0].max(), 100),
                     np.linspace(X_train_pca[:, 1].min(), X_train_pca[:, 1].max(), 100))
Z = best_model.predict(np.c_[xx.ravel(), yy.ravel()])
Z = Z.reshape(xx.shape)

plt.contourf(xx, yy, Z, alpha=0.75)
plt.scatter(X_train_pca[:, 0], X_train_pca[:, 1], c=y_train, s=30, edgecolor='k', cmap='coolwarm')
plt.title("SVC Decision Boundary (PCA-reduced data)")
plt.show()
